Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis pathbreaking collection engages in the important new work of rediscovering the hundreds of British women writing during the Romantic period, women who we now realize were central, not marginal, to the poetics and ideologies of Romanticism. Yet no previous volume has focused on British women's responses to the French Revolution and the Napoleonic wars, or on their participation in the social, economic, religious, and poetic debates surrounding these political conflicts. As the first book to represent the full spectrum of women's participation in the Revolutionary debates, Rebellious Hearts uncovers a rich new field of literary and historical scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aHistory : History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Women Authors.2bisacsh1 aBinfield, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraciun, Adriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraciun, Adriana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGutwirth, Madelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoagwood, Terence Allan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJerinic, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeane, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLokke, Kari E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLokke, Kari E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiller, Judith Davis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoskal, Jean